‐ Jesus, Angela,

296
00:19:21,869 --> 00:19:23,252
not in front of the kids.

297
00:19:23,287 --> 00:19:24,795
GORDY: Mommy,
don’t get mad today.

298
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:26,297
‐ DAD: Yeah, Mommy.
‐ ANGELA: I’m sick of this.

299
00:19:26,332 --> 00:19:28,299
‐ Gordy, open your presents!
‐ GORDY: Mom!

300
00:19:28,334 --> 00:19:29,675
DAD: Go to your room, Gordy.
Your mom and I have to talk.

301
00:19:29,710 --> 00:19:31,052
ANGELA: No. Gordy,
open your present.

302
00:19:31,087 --> 00:19:32,928
‐ ( clatter ) ‐ ( baby crying )

303
00:19:32,963 --> 00:19:34,764
‐ DAD: There! It’s open now!
‐ ANGELA: Daddy opened it.

304
00:19:34,799 --> 00:19:37,099
DAD: A baseball glove!
How fuckin’ original, Mommy!

305
00:19:37,134 --> 00:19:38,976
‐ Go to your room, Gordy.
‐ ANGELA: Don’t touch me.

306
00:19:39,011 --> 00:19:40,645
DAD: You’re the one who has
to make today about you, huh?

307
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:42,229
‐ ANGELA: Just shut up.
‐ DAD: Or what, Angela?!

308
00:19:42,264 --> 00:19:44,106
‐ What are you gonna do?
‐ ( chairs scraping )

309
00:19:44,141 --> 00:19:45,650
‐ I’ll stuff this fuckin’ cake
down your throat.
‐ GORDY: No, Daddy!

310
00:19:45,685 --> 00:19:47,360
ANGELA: I’m gonna kill
you some day.

311
00:19:47,395 --> 00:19:49,278
DAD: Why not today? Huh?
Happy birthday, son.

312
00:19:49,313 --> 00:19:50,821
ANGELA: Say it again,
I’ll cut you open right now,

313
00:19:50,856 --> 00:19:52,823
‐ you son of a bitch.
‐ DAD: Why not today?

314
00:19:52,858 --> 00:19:55,618
‐ ( shouting, screaming )
‐ ( glass breaking )

315
00:19:55,653 --> 00:19:58,037
‐ ( baby crying )
‐ ANGELA: Gordy, run!

316
00:19:58,072 --> 00:20:01,207
‐ ( angry shouting )
‐ ANGELA: Get off me!

317
00:20:01,569 --> 00:20:04,061
( shouting,
screaming continues )

318
00:20:04,979 --> 00:20:07,515
‐ ( stabbing )
‐ ( violent pounding )

319
00:20:09,935 --> 00:20:12,854
‐ ( screaming )
‐ ( fighting continues )

320
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:20,386
‐ ( baby crying )
‐ ( woman moaning )

321
00:20:23,806 --> 00:20:25,558
( baby screeching )

322
00:20:28,789 --> 00:20:30,781
TV: <i>As the blaze
continues to engulf</i>

323
00:20:30,817 --> 00:20:32,851
<i>more and more acres of forest,</i>

324
00:20:32,887 --> 00:20:34,657
<i>Castle County Fire Department</i>

325
00:20:34,692 --> 00:20:36,575
<i>still can’t explain how it began</i>

326
00:20:36,610 --> 00:20:39,036
<i>or why traditional methods
to extinguish the fire</i>

327
00:20:39,071 --> 00:20:40,329
<i>aren’t working.</i>

328
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:41,664
<i>The unusually quick spread</i>

329
00:20:41,699 --> 00:20:43,290
<i>has many convinced</i>

330
00:20:43,325 --> 00:20:45,418
<i>it’s a harbinger
of much worse to come.</i>

331
00:20:45,453 --> 00:20:48,295
<i>And now,
back to the hits you love.</i>

332
00:20:48,330 --> 00:20:50,541
<i>( big band music plays )</i>

333
00:21:03,387 --> 00:21:04,854
Lady on the internet

334
00:21:04,889 --> 00:21:07,022
said they were made by Vikings,

335
00:21:07,057 --> 00:21:08,190
‐ so I figured...
‐ ( gasps )

336
00:21:08,225 --> 00:21:10,686
Oh! The Lewis chessmen?

337
00:21:11,896 --> 00:21:13,529
Oh!

338
00:21:13,564 --> 00:21:14,947
You know, the originals,

339
00:21:14,982 --> 00:21:17,658
they were carved
out of walrus ivory

340
00:21:17,693 --> 00:21:19,452
by the wife of a priest,

341
00:21:19,971 --> 00:21:21,773
Margret the Adroit.

342
00:21:22,523 --> 00:21:24,540
You’re still the smartest person
I know.

343
00:21:24,575 --> 00:21:27,460
Well, smart enough to know
what you’re up to.

344
00:21:27,626 --> 00:21:29,926
‐ ( dog panting )
‐ Come on, girl. Come on.

345
00:21:29,962 --> 00:21:31,923
What else did the internet
teach you?

346
00:21:33,584 --> 00:21:35,676
Chess is good
for the demented brain?

347
00:21:36,015 --> 00:21:37,558
( door closes )

348
00:21:41,509 --> 00:21:42,760
( bell rings )

349
00:22:13,833 --> 00:22:15,084
( light thumping )

350
00:22:27,304 --> 00:22:28,305
Hello?

351
00:22:37,965 --> 00:22:39,359
Hello?

352
00:23:00,421 --> 00:23:01,463
( sniffs )

353
00:23:53,557 --> 00:23:54,683
( sighs )

354
00:23:58,854 --> 00:24:00,189
( grunts )

355
00:24:03,142 --> 00:24:06,062
The rabbit goes...

356
00:24:07,171 --> 00:24:08,370
into the hole.

357
00:24:08,405 --> 00:24:10,915
No, the fox chases the rabbit.

358
00:24:10,950 --> 00:24:13,531
Oh, please.
What’s the difference?

359
00:24:13,953 --> 00:24:16,343
One’s a carnivore,
the other’s breakfast.

360
00:24:17,609 --> 00:24:19,715
God, I haven’t had a tie on

361
00:24:19,750 --> 00:24:22,009
since the day
I turned in my badge.

362
00:24:22,044 --> 00:24:24,011
Mm. You’re so sweet.

363
00:24:24,046 --> 00:24:26,931
It’s not sweet
I can’t tie my tie.

364
00:24:26,966 --> 00:24:28,599
‐ It’s arthritis.
‐ ( chuckles )

365
00:24:28,634 --> 00:24:30,804
Oh, the speech.

366
00:24:31,637 --> 00:24:34,562
You tossed and turned all night.
That’s what kept you up.

367
00:24:35,689 --> 00:24:37,733
There’s no shame in it, Alan.

368
00:24:39,436 --> 00:24:41,612
Stage fright’ll jelly up anyone,

369
00:24:41,647 --> 00:24:43,614
even an Adonis like you.

370
00:24:43,649 --> 00:24:45,783
You’ll do fine, you’ll do fine.

371
00:24:46,037 --> 00:24:48,998
‐ Just picture me naked.
‐ ( laughing )

372
00:24:54,576 --> 00:24:56,412
ALAN:
God, I love you.

373
00:25:02,251 --> 00:25:04,211
Uh... ( clears throat )

374
00:25:06,046 --> 00:25:08,514
I, uh, just need to borrow
the car a few hours.

375
00:25:08,549 --> 00:25:11,600
Oh, sure. You can take it
after Alan’s ceremony.

376
00:25:11,635 --> 00:25:13,769
‐ I wasn’t planning on going.
‐ It’s OK, he doesn’t have to.

377
00:25:13,804 --> 00:25:15,514
I wasn’t askin’.

378
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:34,123
Now, before we get started,

379
00:25:34,158 --> 00:25:37,793
please join me in a moment
of silence for our fallen heroes

380
00:25:37,828 --> 00:25:39,163
at Shawshank.

381
00:25:51,091 --> 00:25:52,808
‐ I wanna testify.
‐ ( gunshot )

382
00:25:52,843 --> 00:25:54,428
( ringing )

383
00:25:58,914 --> 00:26:00,858
Thank you.

384
00:26:01,010 --> 00:26:02,052
Well...

385
00:26:03,479 --> 00:26:05,105
Pangborn Bridge.

386
00:26:07,024 --> 00:26:09,007
Get used to the sound of that.

387
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:11,785
Here’s a man
who has served this county

388
00:26:12,117 --> 00:26:14,578
with honor for decades,

389
00:26:15,534 --> 00:26:18,375
who saw us through some of
our most challenging times...

390
00:26:20,245 --> 00:26:22,664
who never asked
for anything in return,

391
00:26:23,341 --> 00:26:26,428
even when he faced his own
tremendous challenges.

392
00:26:28,337 --> 00:26:30,679
A man who epitomizes
the very soul

393
00:26:30,714 --> 00:26:32,598
of the great town
of Castle Rock.

394
00:26:33,234 --> 00:26:35,184
A man that needs
no introduction from me.

395
00:26:35,219 --> 00:26:36,894
Alan Pangborn, everybody.

396
00:26:36,929 --> 00:26:39,139
( audience clapping )

397
00:26:46,897 --> 00:26:48,614
I guess I oughta
thank the wildfire

398
00:26:48,649 --> 00:26:51,200
for smoking you all
out of your houses.

399
00:26:51,235 --> 00:26:52,694
( mild laughter )

400
00:26:53,658 --> 00:26:54,658
Um...

401
00:26:56,693 --> 00:27:00,038
I wanted to be a magician
when I was a kid.

402
00:27:00,585 --> 00:27:04,331
They always seemed to have a
lovely assistant hanging around.

403
00:27:06,166 --> 00:27:09,460
But, a magician
has to tell a little story.

404
00:27:10,417 --> 00:27:13,294
Something to distract you
while they...

405
00:27:14,216 --> 00:27:16,433
palm an ace off the deck.

406
00:27:16,750 --> 00:27:18,644
I was never any good at that.

407
00:27:18,679 --> 00:27:20,521
Never any good at the patter.

408
00:27:21,070 --> 00:27:23,357
‐ And...
‐ ( dog barking )

409
00:27:23,392 --> 00:27:24,525
( growling, barking )

410
00:27:24,646 --> 00:27:26,105
WOMAN: Quiet!

411
00:27:28,242 --> 00:27:30,757
ALAN: If I’ve done any good
in this town...

412
00:27:31,066 --> 00:27:32,574
‐ ( clears throat )
‐ ( dog continues barking )

413
00:27:32,609 --> 00:27:34,743
If I’ve done any good,
it’s because

414
00:27:34,778 --> 00:27:38,781
of the gift of faith
you people have given me.

415
00:27:39,195 --> 00:27:41,296
‐ ( dog barking )
‐ ALAN: Good people.

416
00:27:41,490 --> 00:27:44,333
I just hope I’ve left
Castle County a little better

417
00:27:44,463 --> 00:27:47,299
‐ than I found it.
‐ ( dog barking )

418
00:27:48,584 --> 00:27:49,668
Ruth?

419
00:27:50,919 --> 00:27:51,919
Ruth!

420
00:27:53,881 --> 00:27:55,264
( dog continues barking )

421
00:27:55,299 --> 00:27:56,299
Mom!

422
00:27:59,803 --> 00:28:01,144
( crowd gasping )

423
00:28:01,179 --> 00:28:02,604
( splashing )

424
00:28:02,639 --> 00:28:04,439
WOMAN:
Oh, no! Somebody help!

425
00:28:04,474 --> 00:28:05,934
( splashing )

426
00:28:10,564 --> 00:28:11,613
( siren wails )

427
00:28:11,648 --> 00:28:13,150
( bell rings )

428
00:28:14,602 --> 00:28:15,985
Hey.

429
00:28:16,153 --> 00:28:17,279
I’m back.

430
00:28:26,914 --> 00:28:28,373
Hello?

431
00:28:30,918 --> 00:28:32,711
( sirens wail in distance )

432
00:29:08,830 --> 00:29:11,089
( sirens continue )

433
00:29:11,460 --> 00:29:16,011
Hey, I don’t know where you are,
but I thought I should tell you,

434
00:29:16,287 --> 00:29:19,255
the kid, um, wandered off.

435
00:29:19,360 --> 00:29:22,780
So, call me when you get this.

436
00:29:24,888 --> 00:29:26,897
JACKIE: Okay, so then
the next‐door neighbors

437
00:29:26,932 --> 00:29:28,857
got gassed in their house.

438
00:29:29,125 --> 00:29:31,695
Just a freak accident,
supposedly.

439
00:29:31,913 --> 00:29:35,340
Cracked furnace case.
They all died in their sleep

440
00:29:35,524 --> 00:29:37,950
on Christmas Eve.
Shit you not.

441
00:29:37,985 --> 00:29:39,611
( music playing )

442
00:29:42,322 --> 00:29:44,282
Lined up the body bags
right on the lawn.

443
00:29:45,409 --> 00:29:46,583
Plus the dog and cat.

444
00:29:47,023 --> 00:29:48,734
This is before I was born.

445
00:29:48,979 --> 00:29:51,299
Just like everything interesting
that’s ever happened here.

446
00:29:56,773 --> 00:29:58,678
I mean, they say
write what you know,

447
00:29:58,714 --> 00:30:00,639
but this town is so blah.

448
00:30:01,281 --> 00:30:03,433
I mean, people bitch
about the bad old days

449
00:30:03,468 --> 00:30:05,227
when there were, like,
serial killers

450
00:30:05,262 --> 00:30:09,546
and psychopathic dogs,
but I would give my left tit

451
00:30:09,808 --> 00:30:12,109
to go back there.

452
00:30:12,144 --> 00:30:13,603
The eighties, man.

453
00:30:18,768 --> 00:30:20,353
I had this uncle, though.

454
00:30:21,862 --> 00:30:23,787
He was a writer, too.

455
00:30:23,822 --> 00:30:25,872
And then, one winter,
he just flipped his lid

456
00:30:25,907 --> 00:30:27,874
and tried to ax‐murder
his wife and kid

457
00:30:27,909 --> 00:30:29,421
at some fancy ski resort.

458
00:30:30,065 --> 00:30:31,968
And my folks will never
talk to me about it.

459
00:30:32,921 --> 00:30:35,773
So I took his name
just to piss them off.

460
00:30:36,421 --> 00:30:38,468
My real name’s Diane.

461
00:30:38,503 --> 00:30:40,262
WOMAN:
<i>We have breaking news.</i>

462
00:30:40,297 --> 00:30:42,305
<i>Less than an hour ago,
a firefighting helicopter</i>

463
00:30:42,340 --> 00:30:45,017
<i>exploded near Castle Lake,
killing the pilot</i>

464
00:30:45,052 --> 00:30:46,977
<i>and two firefighters onboard.</i>

465
00:30:47,012 --> 00:30:48,895
‐ <i>They were attempting...</i>
<i>‐</i> JACKIE: This fucking lighter.

466
00:30:48,930 --> 00:30:50,272
<i>...that originated
on Black Mountain</i>

467
00:30:50,307 --> 00:30:51,982
<i>with flame retardant
when the pilot</i>

468
00:30:52,017 --> 00:30:53,525
<i>apparently lost control
of the aircraft.</i>

469
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:55,318
( Jackie speaks indistinctly )

470
00:30:55,353 --> 00:30:57,612
<i>This tragedy means
five people have now died</i>

471
00:30:57,647 --> 00:30:59,656
<i>as a result
of these powerful fires.</i>

472
00:30:59,691 --> 00:31:01,742
<i>Multiple others
are at County Hospital</i>

473
00:31:01,777 --> 00:31:03,744
<i>being treated for burns,
many of whom</i>

474
00:31:03,779 --> 00:31:05,155
<i>are in critical condition.</i>

475
00:31:17,826 --> 00:31:20,156
It was all they had left
in the machine.

476
00:31:21,542 --> 00:31:23,127
( grunts )

477
00:31:27,928 --> 00:31:30,305
She’s usually OK
in the mornings.

478
00:31:35,060 --> 00:31:36,269
( sighs )

479
00:31:37,479 --> 00:31:39,742
I bought her a ring in ’91.

480
00:31:41,931 --> 00:31:45,906
She said it’d be confusing
to her boy.

481
00:31:47,781 --> 00:31:49,484
And she didn’t deserve it.

482
00:31:50,661 --> 00:31:52,371
Happiness.

483
00:31:55,095 --> 00:31:57,640
Eventually I quit asking
and moved south.

484
00:31:58,197 --> 00:32:00,366
( clears throat )
Live free or die.

485
00:32:03,004 --> 00:32:06,296
By the time I moved back,
I figured we’d missed our shot.

486
00:32:07,245 --> 00:32:09,648
I was an old fuck anyway.

487
00:32:12,013 --> 00:32:14,046
Then I get a phone call.

488
00:32:15,343 --> 00:32:18,289
Somebody heard gunfire up
at your mom’s place.

489
00:32:19,187 --> 00:32:22,280
I wasn’t sheriff, but folks
still rang me up time to time.

490
00:32:22,315 --> 00:32:23,483
Gunfire?

491
00:32:25,318 --> 00:32:26,368
What happened?

492
00:32:26,403 --> 00:32:28,328
Your mother came to the door

493
00:32:28,363 --> 00:32:30,734
looking like she’d been
to hell and back,

494
00:32:31,468 --> 00:32:32,916
threw her arms around me,

495
00:32:32,951 --> 00:32:35,078
begged me, "Don’t leave."

496
00:32:38,456 --> 00:32:39,456
( exhales )

497
00:32:44,269 --> 00:32:46,312
I thought I could keep her safe.

498
00:32:51,609 --> 00:32:52,777
She’s awake.

499
00:33:00,490 --> 00:33:02,367
( knocking )

500
00:33:04,774 --> 00:33:06,359
Oh.

501
00:33:07,454 --> 00:33:09,164
You gotta get back to them.

502
00:33:11,359 --> 00:33:12,507
The naming.

503
00:33:13,414 --> 00:33:14,791
I ruined the party.

504
00:33:14,826 --> 00:33:16,459
ALAN: No, you didn’t.

505
00:33:16,494 --> 00:33:19,080
You didn’t ruin anything.

506
00:33:33,300 --> 00:33:35,803
It was the damn dog.

507
00:33:37,401 --> 00:33:39,148
Nothing stays dead in this town.

508
00:33:40,852 --> 00:33:41,937
( sighs )

509
00:33:45,482 --> 00:33:48,068
It’s like I opened the book
and all the pictures...

510
00:33:51,599 --> 00:33:53,435
someone tore them out.

511
00:33:55,220 --> 00:33:56,555
Rearranged them.

512
00:34:15,996 --> 00:34:17,905
You know how it feels,
don’t you?

513
00:34:19,697 --> 00:34:21,074
To forget your own story.

514
00:34:35,407 --> 00:34:36,407
( brakes squeal )

515
00:34:40,578 --> 00:34:41,878
I don’t know what happened.

516
00:34:41,913 --> 00:34:43,296
We were just shooting the shit.

517
00:34:43,331 --> 00:34:44,331
Where is he?

518
00:35:03,101 --> 00:35:06,382
<i>‐ ( couple screaming )
‐ ( dog barking )</i>

519
00:35:07,300 --> 00:35:09,434
<i>‐ ( baby crying )
‐ ( car strikes object )</i>

520
00:35:09,961 --> 00:35:12,233
<i>‐ ( mysterious whispering )
‐ ( woman moaning )</i>

521
00:35:13,486 --> 00:35:15,370
ZALEWSKI: <i>We’re both
getting out...</i>

522
00:35:15,421 --> 00:35:18,090
<i>Make a fist
and bump it against mine.</i>

523
00:35:23,038 --> 00:35:24,438
MOLLY: I didn’t know
where you went.

524
00:35:24,510 --> 00:35:27,102
I was‐‐ I was worried about you.

525
00:35:27,199 --> 00:35:29,493
<i>‐ ( dog barking )
‐ ( woman screaming )</i>

526
00:35:34,382 --> 00:35:35,942
SHAWSHANK PRISONER:
I shouldn’t be here.

527
00:35:37,093 --> 00:35:38,803
I should still be in the hole.

528
00:35:40,383 --> 00:35:43,023
No, listen to me.

529
00:35:44,023 --> 00:35:46,985
Warden Lacy was just
a sick old man.

530
00:35:47,773 --> 00:35:49,539
Whatever he said to you,

531
00:35:50,429 --> 00:35:52,021
it wasn’t true.

532
00:35:52,257 --> 00:35:55,410
<i>‐ ( panicked shouting )
‐ ( flames erupting )</i>

533
00:35:55,445 --> 00:35:57,996
<i>‐ ( gunshot )
‐ ( indistinct speaking )</i>

534
00:35:58,031 --> 00:35:59,414
LACY:
<i>...the stain.</i>

535
00:35:59,449 --> 00:36:02,042
‐ You’re just a kid.
‐ <i>( screaming )</i>

536
00:36:02,077 --> 00:36:04,412
<i>‐ ( baby crying )
‐ ( people screaming )</i>

537
00:36:11,750 --> 00:36:13,475
‐ MARET: <i>You okay?</i>
‐ HENRY Yeah. Just...

538
00:36:14,714 --> 00:36:17,429
I want Wendell to be able
to remember her when she’s gone,

539
00:36:17,467 --> 00:36:19,351
and I don’t know how much longer

540
00:36:19,386 --> 00:36:21,770
she’ll be able to recognize him.

541
00:36:21,805 --> 00:36:23,730
<i>I guess he could
take a bus up there.</i>

542
00:36:23,765 --> 00:36:26,226
I really appreciate it, Maret.

543
00:36:35,318 --> 00:36:38,196
‐ ( beeps ) ‐ <i>Front door open.</i>

544
00:36:50,937 --> 00:36:52,148
MOLLY:
Henry.

545
00:36:57,991 --> 00:36:58,991
Molly.

546
00:37:02,989 --> 00:37:04,456
I tried calling you.

547
00:37:04,492 --> 00:37:05,820
I’m sorry, my phone is‐‐

548
00:37:06,842 --> 00:37:09,010
( sighs )
It’s a long story.

549
00:37:10,478 --> 00:37:12,171
How did you get in?

550
00:37:13,006 --> 00:37:15,384
There’s a key under the frog.

551
00:37:18,624 --> 00:37:22,460
So I found him on top
of the old shirt factory...

552
00:37:23,158 --> 00:37:25,625
on, you know, I thought
he was gonna jump.

553
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:26,660
Whew.

554
00:37:28,078 --> 00:37:29,045
Had to give him an Oxy

555
00:37:29,080 --> 00:37:30,714
just to get him in the car.

556
00:37:30,749 --> 00:37:32,625
He’s still in there.
He’s sleeping it off.

557
00:37:38,173 --> 00:37:39,674
He feels wrong.

558
00:37:41,696 --> 00:37:44,640
Well, thank you
for getting him settled down.

559
00:37:44,804 --> 00:37:46,855
I think maybe we just need
to get some rest, and‐‐

560
00:37:47,171 --> 00:37:50,340
OK. Um, so I’m not
explaining it right. Um...

561
00:38:00,517 --> 00:38:04,202
Everyone broadcasts
at their own frequency.

562
00:38:05,158 --> 00:38:09,294
Sometimes it’s deafening,
you know, like with you.

563
00:38:09,329 --> 00:38:13,298
Sometimes it’s so faint
I can barely hear it.

564
00:38:13,333 --> 00:38:16,920
But after years of this,
I’ve heard it all.

565
00:38:19,297 --> 00:38:22,390
With him, it’s just‐‐

566
00:38:22,425 --> 00:38:25,185
it’s like I was listening
to the pain of everyone

567
00:38:25,220 --> 00:38:26,679
in this town all at once.

568
00:38:28,348 --> 00:38:29,599
OK.

569
00:38:37,482 --> 00:38:39,741
‐ ( sighs )
‐ Oh, you don’t believe me.

570
00:38:39,776 --> 00:38:41,284
No, no, no, I do. I do.

571
00:38:41,319 --> 00:38:43,154
I just...

572
00:38:44,781 --> 00:38:47,116
Look, I don’t know
what to say to that.

573
00:38:51,412 --> 00:38:53,460
Your right ear is ringing.

574
00:38:54,082 --> 00:38:56,656
So loud you can barely
hear yourself think.

575
00:38:58,173 --> 00:39:01,053
You feel guilty about
the clients you couldn’t save,

576
00:39:01,297 --> 00:39:03,306
about those dead prison guards,

577
00:39:03,632 --> 00:39:05,757
about your mom, and your father,

578
00:39:05,793 --> 00:39:07,962
and <i>your</i> son,
who barely has a father.

579
00:39:10,259 --> 00:39:12,678
And you haven’t eaten yet today.

580
00:39:18,940 --> 00:39:20,359
I’m telling you,

581
00:39:21,025 --> 00:39:24,035
there is something wrong
with that kid.

582
00:39:24,070 --> 00:39:26,322
‐ ( door opens )
‐ <i>Front door open.</i>

583
00:39:38,876 --> 00:39:40,593
Maybe you should
stay here tonight.

584
00:39:41,490 --> 00:39:42,718
Hmm?

585
00:39:43,511 --> 00:39:44,971
Come on.

586
00:40:38,738 --> 00:40:40,812
HENRY: My dad spent
a lot of time out here.

587
00:40:43,716 --> 00:40:46,140
It’s not the Ritz,
but it has a pull‐out.

588
00:40:54,994 --> 00:40:56,579
At least it used to.

589
00:41:30,480 --> 00:41:32,273
Make yourself at home.

590
00:41:41,457 --> 00:41:43,167
Now...

591
00:41:45,378 --> 00:41:46,843
you need anything...

592
00:41:49,514 --> 00:41:50,898
you just cross the yard.

593
00:41:59,642 --> 00:42:01,310
( plays single note )

594
00:42:08,484 --> 00:42:12,113
( plays simple melody )

595
00:42:18,619 --> 00:42:22,373
( plays classical cadence )

596
00:42:28,629 --> 00:42:31,174
( continues playing )

597
00:42:33,634 --> 00:42:34,886
You play piano.

598
00:42:39,585 --> 00:42:41,460
Huh. That’s somethin’.

599
00:42:42,421 --> 00:42:43,984
SHAWSHANK PRISONER:
I remember.

600
00:42:48,876 --> 00:42:51,170
It’ll all come back to you
before you know it.

601
00:43:11,881 --> 00:43:13,389
( Alan grunts )

602
00:43:13,658 --> 00:43:15,785
A fuckin’ bridge.

603
00:43:24,018 --> 00:43:25,394
( splashes )

604
00:43:30,617 --> 00:43:33,910
RUTH: <i>Well, I may be half
bombed, but I coulda sworn...</i>

605
00:43:33,945 --> 00:43:36,788
ALAN: <i>You’re still
the smartest person I know.</i>

606
00:43:36,823 --> 00:43:38,081
<i>( Ruth and Alan laughing )</i>

607
00:43:38,116 --> 00:43:40,201
<i>( phone buzzing )</i>

608
00:44:23,619 --> 00:44:25,371
ALAN:
Hey, asshole.

609
00:44:38,843 --> 00:44:41,262
Do you know who I am?

610
00:44:45,600 --> 00:44:48,811
Don’t look at me like that,
fucker. You know me.

611
00:44:50,188 --> 00:44:51,875
You remember.

612
00:44:52,398 --> 00:44:54,066
( siren bleating )

613
00:44:56,133 --> 00:44:59,194
<i>That’s right. Lacy.</i>

614
00:45:01,570 --> 00:45:04,640
<i>I pulled him over
in the middle of the night.</i>

615
00:45:05,036 --> 00:45:07,086
( banging, muffled shouting )

616
00:45:07,617 --> 00:45:11,424
<i>Wear a badge long enough
in this fuckin’ county,</i>

617
00:45:11,459 --> 00:45:13,551
<i>guy with the Devil
in his Lincoln</i>

618
00:45:13,586 --> 00:45:16,262
<i>doesn’t sound half
bug‐shit crazy.</i>

619
00:45:16,867 --> 00:45:19,286
He asked me to trust him.

620
00:45:20,343 --> 00:45:22,678
God help me, I did.

621
00:45:24,263 --> 00:45:26,439
I used to dream about you.

622
00:45:27,007 --> 00:45:30,526
I can’t remember
my own dead wife’s face,

623
00:45:30,561 --> 00:45:32,695
but I <i>never</i> forgot yours.

624
00:45:32,980 --> 00:45:36,250
Not for 27 fucking years.

625
00:45:42,924 --> 00:45:44,936
Don’t think I didn’t wonder.

626
00:45:46,640 --> 00:45:50,396
<i>Should I let a monster drive
off with a boy in his trunk?</i>

627
00:45:50,432 --> 00:45:52,142
( muffled shouting )

628
00:45:55,836 --> 00:45:58,012
( banging on trunk from inside )

629
00:45:58,695 --> 00:46:00,851
Now I’m an old man,

630
00:46:01,900 --> 00:46:05,234
and you haven’t aged
one goddamn day.

631
00:46:10,296 --> 00:46:11,476
Are you the Devil?

632
00:46:16,156 --> 00:46:17,156
No.

633
00:46:17,592 --> 00:46:19,523
Then what the fuck are you?!

634
00:46:21,174 --> 00:46:22,932
<i>I tried my best.</i>

635
00:46:23,030 --> 00:46:24,664
( clatter )

636
00:46:24,832 --> 00:46:27,351
<i>I tried to keep
the people of this town safe.</i>

637
00:46:29,359 --> 00:46:31,023
<i>Where’s it land you?</i>

638
00:46:32,281 --> 00:46:35,015
You wait 30 years
for the woman you love

639
00:46:36,111 --> 00:46:37,851
and finally you get her,

640
00:46:38,822 --> 00:46:41,078
and she slips through
your fingers.

641
00:46:44,889 --> 00:46:47,804
And here you are,
fuckin’ Rip Van Winkle.

642
00:46:49,682 --> 00:46:51,875
Where’s the justice in that?

643
00:46:55,874 --> 00:46:56,882
( cocks pistol )

644
00:46:56,918 --> 00:46:58,968
I asked you a fuckin’ question.

645
00:47:04,886 --> 00:47:06,242
I can help her.

646
00:47:15,222 --> 00:47:17,562
You have no idea
what’s happening here, do you?

647
00:47:31,265 --> 00:47:32,975
<i>( music playing )</i>

